Other schedulers: at, and systemd timers.

Cron is for things that repeat, but sometimes you want a command to run just once, at a future moment. That is what the at command is for. You feed it a command and a time, and it runs it then and forgets it. Its time language is wonderfully flexible: now plus one hour, three in the morning tomorrow, two p-m on friday, or a specific date and time. You can list the pending jobs with at-q and remove one with at-r-m. Many distributions do not install at by default, so you may need to add it first.

The modern alternative, on the systemd-based systems that are now almost everywhere, is the systemd timer. A timer is described by a timer unit file, paired with a service unit that does the actual work. The timer says when, using a human-readable schedule like daily, and the service says what, by naming the command to run. You can also tell a timer to be persistent, so that if the machine was switched off when a run was due, it catches up on the missed run at the next boot. Once both files are in place, you enable the timer, and you can list all timers to see when each will next fire.

Systemd timers have real advantages over cron. All their output goes to the central journal, so there is one place to look. The persistent option recovers missed runs, which plain cron cannot do. The scheduling syntax is richer, able to fire a set time after boot or after a unit last ran. They can carry resource limits, capping the see-pee-you or memory of a scheduled job. And they are easy to test, since you can simply start the service by hand to run it immediately. For the exam, know cron deeply and understand systemd timers at a preview level; the full story of systemd comes later.
